'''Durave''' or '''Durava'''  are Southern coastal [[Caste system in Sri Lanka|Sinhalese caste]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. Many believes that they are descendants of the ancient [[Naga people (Lanka)|Nagas]], of royalty and aristocracy, of soldiers and elephanteers.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sunday Observer |date=2 September 2001 |url=http://www.infolanka.com/org/srilanka/cult/54.htm |title=The Durava: Toddy tappers or royalty? |first=Asiff |last=Hussein |accessdate=2015-06-09}}</ref>

==Current status==
They were converted to Catholic religion soon after arrival of [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] colonials in 1505 ACE. Using this opportunity they have upgraded themselves in relation to the dominant [[Govigama]] caste.{{cn|date=January 2016}}

They along with other southern Sinhalese castes such as [[Karave]]  and [[Salagama]] have played an important role in the historically left political and right parties. They are mostly [[Theravada]] Buddhists today and were instrumental in the revival of Buddhism during the British colonial period. The un-Buddhistic practice of caste discrimination introduced into the [[Sangha (Buddhism)|Sangha]] by the [[Siyam Nikaya]] in the late 18th century has been overcome by patronising the [[Amarapura Nikaya]] and the [[Ramanna Nikaya]]s. Sitinamaluwe Dhammajoti (Durawa) was the last nongovigama monk to receive upasampada before the 1764 [[List of conspiracies (political)|conspiracy]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Buddhism in Sinhalese Society, 1750-1900: A Study of Religious Revival and Change |first=Kitsiri |last=Malalgoda |page=91 |isbn=978-0-52002-873-9 |publisher=University of California Press |url=http://www.ucpress.edu/op.php?isbn=9780520028739 |year=1976}}</ref>

