'''Iraqi Lurs''' ({{lang-ar|الوار العراق}}, [[Lurish language|Lurish]]:'''لوره یل عیراق''') also referred to as '''Lurs in Iraq''' refers to ethnic Iranian people living in Iraq. Iraqi Lurs are a group of [[Feyli Lurs]] located mainly in Baghdad,<ref>F.J.Darah, 2013, Failis: the Curse of Compound Identity and Scars of Collective Memory, in : Minorities in Iraq. Memory, identity and challenges, edited by Sa’ad Salloum, Masarat for cultural and Media development, Bagdad-Beyrouth, 2013, (in French, Arabic and English languages). pages;112-126</ref> Wassit<ref>http://www.ncciraq.org/images/infobygov/NCCI_Wassit_Governorate_Profile.pdf</ref> and the Diyala Province of Iraq around Mandali, [[Khaneqin]] <ref>Leezenberg, Michiel. 1993. Gorani Influence on Central Kurdish: Substratum or Prestige Borrowing? [Internet] http://www.cogsci.ed.ac.uk [Accessed 15 Feb. 1999] </ref> and across the Iranian border.<ref name="H. Field 1939">H. Field, Contributions to the Anthropology of Iran, Chicago, 1939.</ref><ref>G. R. Fazel, ‘Lur’, in Muslim Peoples: A World Ethnographic Survey, ed. R. V. Weekes (Westport, 1984), pp. 446–447; S. Amanollahi, Qom-e Lor (Tehran, 1991), p. 8</ref> They know themselves as Feylis and also Feyli Kurds. However, they are considered as [[Kurds|Kurdish]] [[Lurs]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faylee.org/?article=455|title=مظلومية الكورد الفيليين عبر التاريخ ومحنة الانتماء الوطني والقومي / طه نعمت|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=R. Izady|first=Mehrdad |title=The Sharafnam̂a, or, The history of the Kurdish nation, 1597|year=2005|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U50sAQAAIAAJ&q=Sharaf+al-Din+Bitlisi&dq=Sharaf+al-Din+Bitlisi&hl=no&ei=JAo2ToeoH86Rswbc9-G5Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA}}</ref> by themselves. Soane (1926), mentioned presence of Feyli Lurs in [[Kirkuk]] [[bazaar]]s.<ref>E.B. Soane, To Mesopotamia and Kurdistan in disguise, with historical Notices of the Kurdish Tribes and the Chaldeans of Kurdistan, (London: John Murray, 1926) (II), 120-124</ref> In 1920, Lurs were 4.3% of [[Nasiriyah]] city, in Southern Iraq.<ref name="FMNH258">Field Museum of Natural History, 1940, p. 258.</ref> [[Freya Stark]] (1932 and 1934) referred to [[Lurs|Lurish]] residence in Iraq and mentioned the Iraqi Lurs as the most beautiful inhabitants of [[Baghdad]].<ref>F.Stark, 1934, ''The Valleys of the Assassins: and Other Persian Travels'', Modern library</ref><ref>F. Stark, 1932, Baghdad Sketches (Travel), Marlboro Press</ref>
==Demographics== The exact number of Iraqi Lurs is unknown, due to the absence of recent and extensive census data but some sources evaluated their population from 80000<ref name="Erik John Anonby 2003 pp 171-197"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prayway.com/unreached/peoplegroups/1837.html|title=Luri of Iraq|publisher=}}</ref> to 150000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplegroups.org/Explore/groupdetails.aspx?peid=11717 |title=Luri |publisher=PeopleGroups.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/49749d09c.html|title=Refworld - World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples - Iraq : Kurds|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|last=Refugees|publisher=}}</ref> people. rv ==Language== Iraqi Lurs speak Feyli, a language that belongs to the [[Lurish language]] and includes [[Laki dialect|Laki]] and Kelhuri dialects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.ethnologue.com/14/show_country.asp?name=Iraq|title=Ethnologue 14 report for Iraq|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peoplegroups.org/explore/GroupDetails.aspx?peid=11717#topmenupeid=11717#topmenu|title=PeopleGroups.org - Laki of Iraq|first=|last=PeopleGroups.org|publisher=}}</ref> [[Feyli language|Feyli]] is spoken particularly on both sides of the border areas between Iraq and Iran.<ref name="H. Field 1939"/> Schmitt (1989), cited [[Baghdadi Lurish]] as an Iranian language spoken in Iraq.<ref>Schmitt, Rüdiger (ed.) (1989). ''Compendium Linguarum Iranicarum'' (in German). Wiesbaden: Reichert. {{ISBN|3-88226-413-6}}</ref>
==Contemporary history== In Iraq,especially during Baath regime the political situation has been disastrous and tragic toward the Lurs.<ref name="Erik John Anonby 2003 pp 171-197">Erik John Anonby (2003). Update on Luri: How many languages?. Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society (Third Series), 13, pp 171-197. doi:10.1017/S1356186303003067.</ref> Since 1975,political factors have resulted in the mass migration of most Iraqi Lurs to Iran, where they share a greater degree of ethnic and religious affinity with the national population. The existence of the Lurs in Iraq has never been marginal. On the contrary, they have participated in all political, social, cultural, and economical activities.<ref>{{cite book|last1= McDowall|first1= David|title=A modern history of the Kurds|year=2004|edition=3rd|publisher= I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781850434160|page=329|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgDi9qFT41oC&q=lur#v=snippet&q=habib&f=false}}</ref><ref>Minority Rights Group International, World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples - Iraq : Kurds, October 2014, available at: http://www.refworld.org/docid/49749d09c.html [accessed 25 February 2017]</ref>
